Instead of being marked in MOA or MIL increments, the turret is marked with the proper bullet drop for a 5.56 or .223 round.  The one that is on there is matched for green tip ammo, but if you shoot a different load, you can get a free turret custom made from Burris that is ballistically matched to your exact load. The RT 1200B is used just like a standard size die. Chips are drawn off through a vacuum manifold that clamps to the outside of the special size/trim die. (Vacuum cleaner and hose not included.) title: For Sale/Trade:  Sig Sauer P320 Compact Medium 9mm and 357 SIG
postcontent:
I am consitering selling my 2 month old Sig Sauer P320.  It is the Compact Medium model.  I purchased it as a 9mm with 2 9mm 15 round magazines.  I then purchased, directly from Sig, the 357 Sig updrade.  The upgrade includes a new slide, barrel, Compact Medium frame and 1 13 round 40/357 magazine. Both slides have night sights!!! 

What makes the P320 special?  It is an upgrade to the P250 from a few years ago.  The pistol frame is not serialized, it is the trigger pack.  The trigger pack can be put into any of the P320 frames and their slides.  Please look up all the combo's on Sig's website.  The biggest thing about that, you can have ANY combo, but once you own the trigger pack, you can add any frame, slide, and barrel withough having to go through a dealer.

The swap between the two calibers is simple, especially since the 9mm and 357 slide use the same frame, you can litterally change calibers in seconds.  Simply lock the slide to the rear, turn the takedown lever downward, release the slide and remove it.  Take the new slide, put it on, and lock it to the rear.  Rotate the takedown lever to the original position, insert the new magazine, and let the slide lock forward.

I have about 150 rounds through both calibers.  I even worked up a custom load for both 9mm and 357 SIG.  I love this pistol.  It is incredibly accurate, recoil is very managable, even with the kick-happy 357 round.  The 357 workup was pushing 125g Hornady XTPs at almost 1500 fps.  The most accurate load is a little slower at 1440 fps.  

Now, the question would probably be....why get rid of it?  Well, for me, I am just not sure where it fits in.  I thought about waiting for the 45 slide and barrel or getting a sub-combact frame/slide.  I sure don't want to go anything smaller than this with a 357.  I have a M&P Shield 9mm, and a Wilson-ized Beretta M9.

Here is a list of what you get.

2x Sig Sauer Plastic Cases
2x Sig Polymer Compact Medium Frames
1x Sig Serialized Trigger pack (Custom polished trigger group for smoother pull and lower pull weight)
1x Sig 9mm upper w/ night sights (slide, barrel, spring)
2x Sig P250/P320 9mm 15 round Magazine
1x Sig 357 SIG upper w/ night sights (slide, barrel, spring)
1x Sig P250/P350 .40/.357 SIG 13 round Magazine.

I do not NEED to sell it!!!  I also do NOT need help selling it!!!  No, I will not trade a Bursa Thunder and $100 cash for it!!!  Serious offers only please.

Pictures to be posted on 4.27.  My camera is acting funny, so I need to get one from my office.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Springfield Armory 1911 EMP® 9mm
postcontent:
Spent a lot of time searching for and researching this pistol online before making the leap. And even though the specs and reviews told me that this was a compact carry, it didn't matter as I was already sold on the review, construction, and very cool looks of this piece. So, I went ahead and bought it even though I had never had my hands on one.

Wasn't disappointed when it arrived and it without a doubt is the nicest pistol I own. It came with the Cocobolo wood grips (I ordered two pairs of VGRIP replacements - G10 in the pics - makes the grip slightly meatier - and another black pair because I just couldn't decide because they both were pretty cool) 

The trigger is crisp and it comes right up into sight picture with a feel that makes you think it is actually a full size pistol. (no dangling pinky) ... It's one of those pieces that you pick up and it just fits your hand and instantly feels like an extension.

There are only two hundred rounds through it, if that. Not a single failure. If I thought for a second that I had any chance of getting a carry permit, this gun would not be up for sale. I bough it in February, took it to the range twice, showed me why people love 1911s with the nice groups I put together, and cleaned it twice.

But that brings me to my reason for selling it.  It's just not what I was looking for and I can't justify having this much money tied up in a gun that I just will never get a chance to put into the kind of service it was designed for. 

-It comes with three 9 round mags
-The usual holster and mag holders you get with Springfield products.
-Also comes with three pairs of grips. (the original and the two VZ grip sets I added)

My range is MidState Guns in Coventry.  If you are serious and want to see it in person, we can make the deal, no shipping cost, no taxes, .. only the transfer fee.
